{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01Q67g11VBSSjUNP1xkfUoME","type":"tool_result","content":"     1â†’# Cloche Usage\n     2â†’\n     3â†’Cloche runs containerized workflows for autonomous coding agents. You define a\n     4â†’workflow graph in the `.cloche` DSL, Cloche copies your project into a Docker\n     5â†’container, runs the workflow steps (agent prompts and shell scripts), and extracts\n     6â†’results to a git branch.\n     7â†’\n     8â†’## Core Concepts\n     9â†’\n    10â†’- **Workflow**: A directed graph of steps connected by named-result wiring.\n    11â†’- **Step**: A unit of work. Type is inferred: `prompt` = agent step, `run` = script step, `workflow_name` = workflow step (host only).\n    12â†’- **Result**: A named outcome reported by a step (e.g. `success`, `fail`, `needs-research`). Steps declare their possible results; the engine follows wiring based on the reported result.\n    13â†’- **Wiring**: Maps `step:result` pairs to the next step. Separate from step definitions.\n    14â†’- **Terminals**: `done` (success) and `abort` (failure) are built-in terminal targets.\n    15â†’\n    16â†’## Workflow DSL\n    17â†’\n    18â†’Workflow files use the `.cloche` extension and live in `.cloche/`. The first step\n    19â†’declared is the entry point. Graphs are validated at parse time (all results wired,\n    20â†’no orphans, entry point exists).\n    21â†’\n    22â†’### Minimal Example\n    23â†’\n    24â†’```\n    25â†’workflow \"develop\" {\n    26â†’  step implement {\n    27â†’    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n    28â†’    results = [success, fail]\n    29â†’  }\n    30â†’\n    31â†’  step test {\n    32â†’    run = \"make test 2>&1\"\n    33â†’    results = [success, fail]\n    34â†’  }\n    35â†’\n    36â†’  implement:success -> test\n    37â†’  implement:fail -> abort\n    38â†’  test:success -> done\n    39â†’  test:fail -> abort\n    40â†’}\n    41â†’```\n    42â†’\n    43â†’### Step Configuration\n    44â†’\n    45â†’| Key | Type | Description |\n    46â†’|-----|------|-------------|\n    47â†’| `prompt` | string or `file(\"path\")` | Prompt template. Makes this an agent step. |\n    48â†’| `run` | string | Shell command. Makes this a script step. |\n    49â†’| `workflow_name` | string | Container workflow to dispatch. Makes this a workflow step (host only). |\n    50â†’| `results` | ident list | Declared result names, e.g. `[success, fail, give-up]`. |\n    51â†’| `max_attempts` | string | Max retries before automatic `give-up` result, e.g. `\"2\"`. |\n    52â†’| `timeout` | string | Step timeout as Go duration, e.g. `\"30m\"`, `\"2h\"`. Default: 30m. |\n    53â†’| `agent_command` | string | Agent binary name(s), comma-separated for fallback chains, e.g. `\"claude,gemini\"`. |\n    54â†’| `agent_args` | string | Override default agent arguments. |\n    55â†’| `feedback` | string | Set to `\"true\"` to include `.cloche/output/*.log` content in the prompt. |\n    56â†’| `prompt_step` | string | For workflow steps: which preceding step's output to use as the prompt. |\n    57â†’\n    58â†’A step must have exactly one of `prompt`, `run`, or `workflow_name`.\n    59â†’\n    60â†’### The `file()` Function\n    61â†’\n    62â†’`file(\"path\")` reads the file at the given path relative to the working directory\n    63â†’(`/workspace/` in containers) at execution time, not parse time. Use it for prompt\n    64â†’templates:\n    65â†’\n    66â†’```\n    67â†’prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n    68â†’```\n    69â†’\n    70â†’### The `container {}` Block\n    71â†’\n    72â†’Can appear at step level or workflow level. Keys are stored with a `container.` prefix.\n    73â†’\n    74â†’**Step level** â€” per-step container config:\n    75â†’```\n    76â†’step code {\n    77â†’  prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n    78â†’  container {\n    79â†’    image         = \"custom-agent:v2\"\n    80â†’    memory        = \"4g\"\n    81â†’    network_allow = [\"docs.python.org\", \"api.example.com\"]\n    82â†’  }\n    83â†’  results = [success, fail]\n    84â†’}\n    85â†’```\n    86â†’\n    87â†’**Workflow level** â€” defaults for all steps:\n    88â†’```\n    89â†’workflow \"develop\" {\n    90â†’  container {\n    91â†’    agent_command = \"gemini\"\n    92â†’    image         = \"myregistry/myimage:v2\"\n    93â†’    memory        = \"4g\"\n    94â†’  }\n    95â†’  ...\n    96â†’}\n    97â†’```\n    98â†’\n    99â†’Supported keys: `image`, `memory`, `network_allow`, `agent_command`, `agent_args`.\n   100â†’\n   101â†’### The `host {}` Block\n   102â†’\n   103â†’Can appear at workflow level in host workflows (`.cloche/host.cloche`). Keys are stored\n   104â†’with a `host.` prefix. Configures agent defaults for agent steps running on the host.\n   105â†’\n   106â†’```\n   107â†’workflow \"main\" {\n   108â†’  host {\n   109â†’    agent_command = \"claude\"\n   110â†’  }\n   111â†’  ...\n   112â†’}\n   113â†’```\n   114â†’\n   115â†’Supported keys: `agent_command`, `agent_args`. Step-level `agent_command` and\n   116â†’`agent_args` config keys override the workflow-level `host {}` defaults.\n   117â†’\n   118â†’### Wiring Syntax\n   119â†’\n   120â†’Connect steps with `step:result -> next_step`:\n   121â†’\n   122â†’```\n   123â†’implement:success -> test\n   124â†’implement:fail -> abort\n   125â†’test:success -> done\n   126â†’test:fail -> fix\n   127â†’```\n   128â†’\n   129â†’### Wire Output Mappings\n   130â†’\n   131â†’Extract values from a step's JSON output and inject as env vars into the target:\n   132â†’\n   133â†’```\n   134â†’step-a:success -> step-b [ ENV_VAR = output.field, OTHER = output.list[0].name ]\n   135â†’```\n   136â†’\n   137â†’Path expressions:\n   138â†’\n   139â†’| Expression | Meaning |\n   140â†’|---|---|\n   141â†’| `output` | Raw output (full string) |\n   142â†’| `output.key` | JSON object field access |\n   143â†’| `output[N]` | JSON array index (0-based) |\n   144â†’| `output.a.b.c` | Deeply nested field access |\n   145â†’| `output.items[0].name` | Mixed field and index chaining |\n   146â†’\n   147â†’If the output is valid JSON, path expressions navigate the structure. If it's plain\n   148â†’text, only bare `output` works.\n   149â†’\n   150â†’### Retry Loops\n   151â†’\n   152â†’Wire failures back to earlier steps:\n   153â†’\n   154â†’```\n   155â†’test:fail -> fix\n   156â†’fix:success -> test    // retry the test\n   157â†’fix:fail -> abort\n   158â†’```\n   159â†’\n   160â†’Use `max_attempts` to cap retries. When exhausted, the step returns `give-up`:\n   161â†’\n   162â†’```\n   163â†’step fix {\n   164â†’  prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/fix.md\")\n   165â†’  max_attempts = \"2\"\n   166â†’  results = [success, fail, give-up]\n   167â†’}\n   168â†’```\n   169â†’\n   170â†’### Parallel Branches (Fanout)\n   171â†’\n   172â†’Wire one result to multiple targets for concurrent execution:\n   173â†’\n   174â†’```\n   175â†’test:success -> lint\n   176â†’test:success -> quality\n   177â†’```\n   178â†’\n   179â†’### Collect (Join)\n   180â†’\n   181â†’Synchronize parallel branches:\n   182â†’\n   183â†’```\n   184â†’collect all(lint:success, quality:success) -> done\n   185â†’collect any(lint:success, quality:success) -> done\n   186â†’```\n   187â†’\n   188â†’`all` fires when every condition is met. `any` fires when at least one is.\n   189â†’\n   190â†’### Comments\n   191â†’\n   192â†’Line comments with `//`:\n   193â†’\n   194â†’```\n   195â†’// This is a comment\n   196â†’implement:success -> test  // inline comment\n   197â†’```\n   198â†’\n   199â†’## Result Protocol\n   200â†’\n   201â†’Steps report results by printing a marker line to stdout:\n   202â†’\n   203â†’```\n   204â†’CLOCHE_RESULT:<name>\n   205â†’```\n   206â†’\n   207â†’For example: `CLOCHE_RESULT:success`, `CLOCHE_RESULT:needs-research`, `CLOCHE_RESULT:give-up`.\n   208â†’\n   209â†’Rules:\n   210â†’- The **last** `CLOCHE_RESULT:` line wins if multiple are printed.\n   211â†’- Marker lines are **stripped** from captured output (not passed to logs or downstream steps).\n   212â†’- The result name must match one of the step's declared `results`.\n   213â†’- For script steps with no marker: exit 0 = `success`, exit non-zero = `fail`.\n   214â†’- For agent steps: if exit non-zero with a marker, the marker result is used. If exit non-zero without a marker, falls back to the next agent in the fallback chain (or returns `fail` if last).\n   215â†’\n   216â†’## Prompt Assembly\n   217â†’\n   218â†’When an agent step runs, Cloche assembles a prompt from these sections (joined by blank lines):\n   219â†’\n   220â†’1. **Step template**: The step's `prompt` content (inline string or resolved `file(\"path\")`).\n   221â†’2. **User request**: Content of `.cloche/<run-id>/prompt.txt` (set via `--prompt` flag), prefixed with `## User Request`.\n   222â†’3. **Validation output** (opt-in): If `feedback = \"true\"`, reads all `.log` files from `.cloche/output/` and includes them prefixed with `## Validation Output`.\n   223â†’4. **Result selection**: Lists the step's declared results with instructions to print exactly one `CLOCHE_RESULT:<name>` marker.\n   224â†’\n   225â†’The assembled prompt is passed to the agent command via stdin.\n   226â†’\n   227â†’## Agent Command Resolution\n   228â†’\n   229â†’Priority (highest to lowest):\n   230â†’1. Step-level `agent_command`\n   231â†’2. Workflow-level config block (`container { agent_command }` for container workflows, `host { agent_command }` for host workflows)\n   232â†’3. `CLOCHE_AGENT_COMMAND` environment variable\n   233â†’4. Default: `claude`\n   234â†’\n   235â†’### Fallback Chains\n   236â†’\n   237â†’Comma-separated commands are tried in order:\n   238â†’\n   239â†’```\n   240â†’agent_command = \"claude,gemini,codex\"\n   241â†’```\n   242â†’\n   243â†’- **Command not found / failed to start** â€” try next command\n   244â†’- **Exit non-zero without `CLOCHE_RESULT` marker** â€” try next command\n   245â†’- **Exit non-zero with `CLOCHE_RESULT` marker** â€” use that result (no fallback)\n   246â†’- **Exit 0** â€” use result (no fallback)\n   247â†’- **All commands fail to start** â€” step returns an error\n   248â†’- **Last command crashes without marker** â€” step returns `fail`\n   249â†’\n   250â†’Known agents (e.g. `claude`) get default arguments (`-p --output-format stream-json --verbose --dangerously-skip-permissions`). Unknown agents receive the prompt on stdin with no flags. Override with `agent_args`.\n   251â†’\n   252â†’### Agent Setup Guides\n   253â†’\n   254â†’For detailed container setup instructions per agent:\n   255â†’\n   256â†’- [How to set up Claude Code](agent-setup-claude.md) â€” session-based auth, no API key needed\n   257â†’- [How to set up Codex](agent-setup-codex.md) â€” API key configuration\n   258â†’\n   259â†’## Workflow Locations\n   260â†’\n   261â†’**Container workflows** (`.cloche/*.cloche` except `host.cloche`) run inside Docker\n   262â†’via `cloche-agent`. Steps may only be `agent` or `script` type.\n   263â†’\n   264â†’**Host workflow** (`.cloche/host.cloche`) runs on the host machine as the daemon.\n   265â†’Steps may be `agent`, `script`, or `workflow` type. The `workflow_name` step type\n   266â†’dispatches a container workflow run and blocks until it completes. Script steps\n   267â†’execute with their working directory set to the main git worktree, so host-workflow\n   268â†’fixes on main are available to in-flight runs even if they branched earlier.\n   269â†’\n   270â†’A single `host.cloche` file may contain **multiple named workflows**. The daemon\n   271â†’uses up to three workflow phases for orchestration:\n   272â†’\n   273â†’| Phase | Workflow name | Purpose |\n   274â†’|-------|--------------|---------|\n   275â†’| 1 | `list-tasks` | Discover available work. Output is JSONL (one task per line). |\n   276â†’| 2 | `main` | Do the work. Receives a task ID via `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` env var. |\n   277â†’| 3 | `finalize` | Post-main cleanup. Runs on **both** success and failure. |\n   278â†’\n   279â†’Only `main` is required. If `list-tasks` is absent, the daemon uses a single-workflow\n   280â†’mode. If `finalize` is absent, it is skipped.\n   281â†’\n   282â†’### list-tasks Output Format\n   283â†’\n   284â†’The `list-tasks` workflow's final step output is parsed as JSONL. Each line is a JSON\n   285â†’object:\n   286â†’\n   287â†’| Field | Required | Description |\n   288â†’|-------|----------|-------------|\n   289â†’| `id` | yes | Unique task identifier |\n   290â†’| `status` | yes | One of `open`, `closed`, `in-progress` |\n   291â†’| `title` | no | Short summary |\n   292â†’| `description` | no | Full description |\n   293â†’| `metadata` | no | Arbitrary key-value pairs |\n   294â†’\n   295â†’The daemon picks the first task with status `open`, runs `main` with that task's ID\n   296â†’set in `CLOCHE_TASK_ID`, then runs `finalize` with the outcome. Tasks are\n   297â†’deduplicated within a timeout window to prevent rapid reassignment of the same task.\n   298â†’\n   299â†’### Host Workflow Example\n   300â†’\n   301â†’A three-phase `host.cloche`:\n   302â†’\n   303â†’```\n   304â†’workflow \"list-tasks\" {\n   305â†’  step fetch-tickets {\n   306â†’    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/ready-tasks.sh\"\n   307â†’    results = [success, fail]\n   308â†’  }\n   309â†’\n   310â†’  fetch-tickets:success -> done\n   311â†’  fetch-tickets:fail    -> abort\n   312â†’}\n   313â†’\n   314â†’workflow \"main\" {\n   315â†’  host {\n   316â†’    agent_command = \"claude\"\n   317â†’  }\n   318â†’\n   319â†’  step prepare-prompt {\n   320â†’    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/prepare-prompt.sh\"\n   321â†’    results = [success, fail]\n   322â†’  }\n   323â†’\n   324â†’  step develop {\n   325â†’    workflow_name = \"develop\"\n   326â†’    results       = [success, fail]\n   327â†’  }\n   328â†’\n   329â†’  prepare-prompt:success -> develop\n   330â†’  prepare-prompt:fail    -> abort\n   331â†’  develop:success        -> done\n   332â†’  develop:fail           -> done\n   333â†’}\n   334â†’\n   335â†’workflow \"finalize\" {\n   336â†’  step push-for-review {\n   337â†’    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/push-for-review.sh\"\n   338â†’    results = [success, fail]\n   339â†’  }\n   340â†’\n   341â†’  push-for-review:success -> done\n   342â†’  push-for-review:fail    -> done\n   343â†’}\n   344â†’```\n   345â†’\n   346â†’The `list-tasks` script writes JSONL to `$CLOCHE_STEP_OUTPUT`. The `main` workflow\n   347â†’receives the task ID and is responsible for claiming the ticket. The `finalize`\n   348â†’workflow receives `CLOCHE_MAIN_OUTCOME` and `CLOCHE_MAIN_RUN_ID` env vars to decide\n   349â†’what cleanup to perform.\n   350â†’\n   351â†’### Host Step Environment Variables\n   352â†’\n   353â†’| Variable | Description |\n   354â†’|----------|-------------|\n   355â†’| `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR` | Absolute path to the project directory on the host. |\n   356â†’| `CLOCHE_STEP_OUTPUT` | Path where this step should write its output (for output mappings). |\n   357â†’| `CLOCHE_PREV_OUTPUT` | Path to the output file from the immediately preceding step. |\n   358â†’| `CLOCHE_RUN_ID` | The run ID for this workflow execution. |\n   359â†’| `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` | Task ID assigned by the daemon (set for `main` and `finalize` phases). |\n   360â†’| `CLOCHE_MAIN_OUTCOME` | Result of the `main` workflow (`succeeded` or `failed`). Set for `finalize` phase only. |\n   361â†’| `CLOCHE_MAIN_RUN_ID` | Run ID of the completed `main` workflow. Set for `finalize` phase only. |\n   362â†’| Wire-mapped vars | Any env vars declared in wire output mappings. |\n   363â†’\n   364â†’### Container Environment Variables\n   365â†’\n   366â†’| Variable | Description |\n   367â†’|----------|-------------|\n   368â†’| `CLOCHE_RUN_ID` | The run ID for this workflow execution. |\n   369â†’| `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR` | Working directory (set for script steps so `cloche get`/`cloche set` work). |\n   370â†’| `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` | Passed through from the host if set. |\n   371â†’| `CLOCHE_AGENT_COMMAND` | Overrides the default agent command inside the container. |\n   372â†’\n   373â†’## Setting Up Host Workflows\n   374â†’\n   375â†’The `host.cloche` file is the orchestration layer that ties everything together.\n   376â†’When you run `cloche init`, a minimal `host.cloche` with just a `main` workflow is\n   377â†’generated. As your project grows, you can add `list-tasks` and `finalize` workflows\n   378â†’to automate task discovery and cleanup.\n   379â†’\n   380â†’The daemon recognizes three workflow names in `host.cloche` and runs them in order:\n   381â†’\n   382â†’1. **`list-tasks`** â€” discover available work\n   383â†’2. **`main`** â€” execute the work\n   384â†’3. **`finalize`** â€” clean up after the work completes\n   385â†’\n   386â†’All three workflows live in the same `.cloche/host.cloche` file. Only `main` is\n   387â†’required; `list-tasks` and `finalize` are optional.\n   388â†’\n   389â†’### `list-tasks` â€” Discovering Work\n   390â†’\n   391â†’The `list-tasks` workflow runs first. Its job is to query your task tracker (issue\n   392â†’tracker, project board, ticket queue, etc.) and output a list of available tasks.\n   393â†’\n   394â†’**When it runs:** The daemon calls `list-tasks` at the start of each orchestration\n   395â†’loop iteration, before launching any new `main` runs.\n   396â†’\n   397â†’**Output format:** The final step must write JSONL (one JSON object per line) to\n   398â†’`$CLOCHE_STEP_OUTPUT`. Each line represents a task:\n   399â†’\n   400â†’```json\n   401â†’{\"id\": \"PROJ-42\", \"status\": \"open\", \"title\": \"Fix login bug\", \"description\": \"Users report...\"}\n   402â†’{\"id\": \"PROJ-43\", \"status\": \"in-progress\", \"title\": \"Add caching\", \"description\": \"...\"}\n   403â†’{\"id\": \"PROJ-44\", \"status\": \"open\", \"title\": \"Update docs\", \"description\": \"...\"}\n   404â†’```\n   405â†’\n   406â†’The daemon picks the first task with `status: \"open\"` and passes it to `main`.\n   407â†’Tasks that were recently assigned are deduplicated within a timeout window (default\n   408â†’5 minutes) to prevent the same task from being picked repeatedly.\n   409â†’\n   410â†’**How to configure:** Write a script that queries your task source and outputs JSONL:\n   411â†’\n   412â†’```\n   413â†’workflow \"list-tasks\" {\n   414â†’  step fetch-tickets {\n   415â†’    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/ready-tasks.sh\"\n   416â†’    results = [success, fail]\n   417â†’  }\n   418â†’\n   419â†’  fetch-tickets:success -> done\n   420â†’  fetch-tickets:fail    -> abort\n   421â†’}\n   422â†’```\n   423â†’\n   424â†’**If omitted:** The daemon falls back to single-workflow mode â€” it runs `main`\n   425â†’once without task assignment. This is fine for simple use cases where you trigger\n   426â†’runs manually with `cloche run`.\n   427â†’\n   428â†’### `main` â€” Executing Work\n   429â†’\n   430â†’The `main` workflow does the actual work. This is the only required workflow in\n   431â†’`host.cloche` and is always generated by `cloche init`.\n   432â†’\n   433â†’**When it runs:** After `list-tasks` selects a task (or immediately if `list-tasks`\n   434â†’is absent). The daemon sets the `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` environment variable from the\n   435â†’selected task.\n   436â†’\n   437â†’**How to configure:** A typical `main` workflow prepares a prompt from the task data,\n   438â†’then dispatches a container workflow:\n   439â†’\n   440â†’```\n   441â†’workflow \"main\" {\n   442â†’  host {\n   443â†’    agent_command = \"claude\"\n   444â†’  }\n   445â†’\n   446â†’  step prepare-prompt {\n   447â†’    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/prepare-prompt.sh\"\n   448â†’    results = [success, fail]\n   449â†’  }\n   450â†’\n   451â†’  step develop {\n   452â†’    workflow_name = \"develop\"\n   453â†’    prompt_step   = \"prepare-prompt\"\n   454â†’    results       = [success, fail]\n   455â†’  }\n   456â†’\n   457â†’  prepare-prompt:success -> develop\n   458â†’  prepare-prompt:fail    -> abort\n   459â†’  develop:success        -> done\n   460â†’  develop:fail           -> done\n   461â†’}\n   462â†’```\n   463â†’\n   464â†’The `workflow_name` step type dispatches a container workflow run and blocks until\n   465â†’it completes. Use `prompt_step` to specify which preceding step's output should be\n   466â†’used as the prompt for the container run.\n   467â†’\n   468â†’You can add steps before or after the container workflow â€” for example, a\n   469â†’`claim-task` step to mark the task as in-progress in your tracker, or a\n   470â†’`merge-to-main` step to merge the result branch.\n   471â†’\n   472â†’### `finalize` â€” Post-Run Cleanup\n   473â†’\n   474â†’The `finalize` workflow handles cleanup after `main` completes. It runs regardless\n   475â†’of whether `main` succeeded or failed.\n   476â†’\n   477â†’**When it runs:** Immediately after `main` finishes (success or failure). The daemon\n   478â†’sets two additional environment variables:\n   479â†’\n   480â†’- `CLOCHE_MAIN_OUTCOME` â€” `\"succeeded\"` or `\"failed\"`\n   481â†’- `CLOCHE_MAIN_RUN_ID` â€” the run ID of the completed `main` workflow\n   482â†’\n   483â†’**How to configure:** Use the outcome to decide what cleanup to perform:\n   484â†’\n   485â†’```\n   486â†’workflow \"finalize\" {\n   487â†’  step close-task {\n   488â†’    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/close-task.sh\"\n   489â†’    results = [success, fail]\n   490â†’  }\n   491â†’\n   492â†’  close-task:success -> done\n   493â†’  close-task:fail    -> done\n   494â†’}\n   495â†’```\n   496â†’\n   497â†’A typical `finalize` script checks `$CLOCHE_MAIN_OUTCOME` and acts accordingly â€”\n   498â†’closing the ticket on success, or posting a failure comment for investigation.\n   499â†’Wiring both results to `done` (not `abort`) ensures the daemon treats the\n   500â†’finalize phase as complete regardless of the cleanup script's exit status.\n   501â†’\n   502â†’**If omitted:** The daemon skips the finalize phase entirely. This is fine if you\n   503â†’don't need automated cleanup.\n   504â†’\n   505â†’### Putting It All Together\n   506â†’\n   507â†’The three-phase model enables fully automated task pipelines:\n   508â†’\n   509â†’1. The orchestration loop calls `list-tasks` to find open work\n   510â†’2. It picks an open task and launches `main` with the task context\n   511â†’3. `main` prepares a prompt, dispatches a container workflow, and optionally merges results\n   512â†’4. `finalize` closes the ticket or reports failure\n   513â†’5. The loop repeats, picking the next open task\n   514â†’\n   515â†’Start the loop with `cloche loop` and monitor tasks with `cloche tasks`. The\n   516â†’`--max` flag controls how many `main` runs execute concurrently.\n   517â†’\n   518â†’## Complete Example: Container Workflow with Parallel Validation\n   519â†’\n   520â†’```\n   521â†’workflow \"develop\" {\n   522â†’  step implement {\n   523â†’    prompt = file(\"prompts/implement.md\")\n   524â†’    results = [success, fail]\n   525â†’  }\n   526â†’\n   527â†’  step test {\n   528â†’    run = \"bundle exec rake test 2>&1\"\n   529â†’    results = [success, fail]\n   530â†’  }\n   531â†’\n   532â†’  step lint {\n   533â†’    run = \"bundle exec rubocop 2>&1\"\n   534â†’    results = [success, fail]\n   535â†’  }\n   536â†’\n   537â†’  step quality {\n   538â†’    run = \"python3 scripts/quality-check.py 2>&1\"\n   539â†’    results = [success, fail]\n   540â†’  }\n   541â†’\n   542â†’  step fix {\n   543â†’    prompt = file(\"prompts/fix.md\")\n   544â†’    max_attempts = \"2\"\n   545â†’    results = [success, fail, give-up]\n   546â†’  }\n   547â†’\n   548â†’  implement:success -> test\n   549â†’  implement:fail -> abort\n   550â†’\n   551â†’  test:success -> lint\n   552â†’  test:success -> quality\n   553â†’  test:fail -> fix\n   554â†’\n   555â†’  lint:fail -> fix\n   556â†’  quality:fail -> fix\n   557â†’  collect all(lint:success, quality:success) -> done\n   558â†’\n   559â†’  fix:success -> test\n   560â†’  fix:fail -> abort\n   561â†’  fix:give-up -> abort\n   562â†’}\n   563â†’```\n   564â†’\n   565â†’## Container Isolation Model\n   566â†’\n   567â†’- **Files in**: `docker cp` copies the project into `/workspace/`. No bind mounts. Override files from `.cloche/overrides/` are applied on top. `.git/` is included.\n   568â†’- **Files out**: On completion, the daemon extracts results via `docker cp` into a git worktree and commits to a `cloche/<run-id>` branch.\n   569â†’- **Auth files**: `~/.claude/` and `~/.claude.json` are copied into each container at `/home/agent/` for Claude Code session reuse. Copied (not bind-mounted) so each container gets its own isolated copy.\n   570â†’- **Network**: Containers have network access (needed for API calls).\n   571â†’- **Cleanup**: Containers are removed after successful runs unless `--keep-container` is set. Failed runs always keep their container.\n   572â†’\n   573â†’Your project directory is never modified by the container.\n   574â†’\n   575â†’## CLI Reference\n   576â†’\n   577â†’Every subcommand supports `--help` (or `-h`) to show detailed usage, flags, and\n   578â†’examples. Use `cloche help <command>` for the same output:\n   579â†’\n   580â†’```\n   581â†’cloche --help              # top-level overview\n   582â†’cloche help run            # detailed help for \"run\"\n   583â†’cloche run --help          # same as above\n   584â†’```\n   585â†’\n   586â†’### `cloche init`\n   587â†’\n   588â†’Scaffold a new Cloche project.\n   589â†’\n   590â†’```\n   591â†’cloche init [--workflow <name>] [--base-image <base>]\n   592â†’```\n   593â†’\n   594â†’| Flag | Default | Description |\n   595â†’|------|---------|-------------|\n   596â†’| `--workflow <name>` | `develop` | Workflow name. Creates `.cloche/<name>.cloche`. |\n   597â†’| `--base-image <base>` | `cloche-base:latest` | Base Docker image for the generated Dockerfile. |\n   598â†’\n   599â†’Creates `.cloche/` with workflow file, Dockerfile, `config.toml`, prompt templates,\n   600â†’host workflow (`host.cloche`), and prompt generation script. Skips existing files.\n   601â†’\n   602â†’### `cloche run`\n   603â†’\n   604â†’Launch a workflow run.\n   605â†’\n   606â†’```\n   607â†’cloche run --workflow <name> [--prompt \"...\"] [--title \"...\"] [--keep-container]\n   608â†’```\n   609â†’\n   610â†’| Flag | Description |\n   611â†’|------|-------------|\n   612â†’| `--workflow <name>` | Workflow name. Resolves to `.cloche/<name>.cloche`. |\n   613â†’| `--prompt \"...\"`, `-p` | Inline prompt written to `.cloche/<run-id>/prompt.txt`. |\n   614â†’| `--title \"...\"` | One-line summary for status display. Auto-generated if omitted. |\n   615â†’| `--keep-container` | Keep container on success (failed runs always keep it). |\n   616â†’\n   617â†’Must be run from inside a git repository. The daemon auto-rebuilds the Docker image\n   618â†’when `.cloche/Dockerfile` changes.\n   619â†’\n   620â†’### `cloche status`\n   621â†’\n   622â†’```\n   623â†’cloche status <run-id>\n   624â†’```\n   625â†’\n   626â†’Shows run title, type (`host`/`container`), state, active steps, and per-step results.\n   627â†’\n   628â†’### `cloche list`\n   629â†’\n   630â†’```\n   631â†’cloche list [flags]\n   632â†’```\n   633â†’\n   634â†’Lists runs for the current project directory. Pass `--all` to show runs across all projects.\n   635â†’Results can be filtered by state, project, issue, or limited to a fixed number.\n   636â†’\n   637â†’| Flag | Description |\n   638â†’|------|-------------|\n   639â†’| `--all` | Show runs from all projects (default: current project only). |\n   640â†’| `--project, -p DIR` | Filter by project directory. |\n   641â†’| `--state, -s STATE` | Filter by run state (`pending`, `running`, `succeeded`, `failed`, `cancelled`). |\n   642â†’| `--limit, -n NUM` | Limit the number of results returned. |\n   643â†’| `--issue, -i ID` | Filter by issue/task ID. |\n   644â†’\n   645â†’### `cloche logs`\n   646â†’\n   647â†’```\n   648â†’cloche logs <run-id> [--step <name>] [--type <full|script|llm>] [-f]\n   649â†’```\n   650â†’\n   651â†’| Flag | Description |\n   652â†’|------|-------------|\n   653â†’| `--step <name>` | Show only logs for the specified step. |\n   654â†’| `--type <full\\|script\\|llm>` | Log type filter. |\n   655â†’| `-f` | Follow mode: display existing logs then continue streaming new lines as they arrive (like `tail -f`). |\n   656â†’\n   657â†’Without `-f`, displays all logs captured to date and exits (even for active runs). With `-f` on an active run, existing logs are sent first, then new output is streamed in real time via gRPC until the run completes.\n   658â†’\n   659â†’### `cloche poll`\n   660â†’\n   661â†’```\n   662â†’cloche poll <run-id>\n   663â†’```\n   664â†’\n   665â†’Block until the run finishes. Polls every 2 seconds. Exits 0 on success, 1 on failure.\n   666â†’\n   667â†’### `cloche stop`\n   668â†’\n   669â†’```\n   670â†’cloche stop <run-id>\n   671â†’```\n   672â†’\n   673â†’### `cloche delete`\n   674â†’\n   675â†’```\n   676â†’cloche delete <container-or-run-id>\n   677â†’```\n   678â†’\n   679â†’Delete a retained Docker container by container ID or run ID.\n   680â†’\n   681â†’### `cloche health`\n   682â†’\n   683â†’```\n   684â†’cloche health\n   685â†’```\n   686â†’\n   687â†’Show per-project pass/fail summary. Requires `CLOCHE_HTTP`.\n   688â†’\n   689â†’### `cloche workflow`\n   690â†’\n   691â†’```\n   692â†’cloche workflow [--project <dir>]\n   693â†’cloche workflow <name> [--project <dir>]\n   694â†’```\n   695â†’\n   696â†’List all workflows or render a specific workflow as an ASCII-art graph.\n   697â†’\n   698â†’| Flag | Default | Description |\n   699â†’|------|---------|-------------|\n   700â†’| `--project <dir>`, `-p` | current directory | Project directory to search for workflows. |\n   701â†’\n   702â†’With no arguments, lists all workflows grouped by type (container or host). With a\n   703â†’workflow name, renders the workflow graph showing step boxes, wiring, and result paths.\n   704â†’Wires are colorized: green for `success`, red for `fail`/`failed`,\n   705â†’blue/yellow/orange/magenta for other results. Wires to the same destination are merged\n   706â†’for readability.\n   707â†’\n   708â†’### `cloche project`\n   709â†’\n   710â†’Show project info and config.\n   711â†’\n   712â†’```\n   713â†’cloche project [--name <label>]\n   714â†’```\n   715â†’\n   716â†’By default, looks up the project by the current working directory. Use `--name` to look\n   717â†’up a project by its registered label instead.\n   718â†’\n   719â†’| Flag | Default | Description |\n   720â†’|------|---------|-------------|\n   721â†’| `--name <label>` | _(cwd lookup)_ | Look up project by label (e.g. `cloche`) instead of directory. |\n   722â†’\n   723â†’Output includes: config settings (active, concurrency, stagger, dedup, evolution),\n   724â†’orchestrator loop state (running/stopped), currently active runs, and known container\n   725â†’and host workflow names.\n   726â†’\n   727â†’### `cloche get`\n   728â†’\n   729â†’```\n   730â†’cloche get <key>\n   731â†’```\n   732â†’\n   733â†’Get a value from the run context store (`.cloche/<run-id>/context.json`). Requires\n   734â†’the `CLOCHE_RUN_ID` environment variable. Uses `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR` if set, otherwise\n   735â†’the current working directory. Exits 1 if the key is not found.\n   736â†’\n   737â†’### `cloche set`\n   738â†’\n   739â†’```\n   740â†’cloche set <key> <value|->\n   741â†’```\n   742â†’\n   743â†’Set a value in the run context store (`.cloche/<run-id>/context.json`). Requires\n   744â†’the `CLOCHE_RUN_ID` environment variable. Uses `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR` if set, otherwise\n   745â†’the current working directory. Creates the file and directories if they don't exist.\n   746â†’Pass `-` as the value to read from stdin (trailing newlines are trimmed).\n   747â†’\n   748â†’### `cloche tasks`\n   749â†’\n   750â†’```\n   751â†’cloche tasks [--project <dir>]\n   752â†’```\n   753â†’\n   754â†’Show the task pipeline and assignment state for an orchestration loop. Displays\n   755â†’upcoming/open tasks, which tasks are assigned to which runs, and auto-assignment\n   756â†’state. Requires `CLOCHE_HTTP` (talks to the daemon's web API).\n   757â†’\n   758â†’| Flag | Default | Description |\n   759â†’|------|---------|-------------|\n   760â†’| `--project <dir>` | current directory name | Project to query tasks for. |\n   761â†’\n   762â†’### `cloche loop`\n   763â†’\n   764â†’Start or stop the daemon's orchestration loop. The loop automatically picks up\n   765â†’tasks from the pipeline and runs them.\n   766â†’\n   767â†’```\n   768â†’cloche loop [--max <n>]\n   769â†’cloche loop stop\n   770â†’```\n   771â†’\n   772â†’| Flag | Default | Description |\n   773â†’|------|---------|-------------|\n   774â†’| `--max <n>` | config value | Maximum concurrent runs. Defaults to the value in `.cloche/config.toml`. |\n   775â†’\n   776â†’`cloche loop stop` disables the loop. Running tasks are not cancelled.\n   777â†’\n   778â†’### `cloche shutdown`\n   779â†’\n   780â†’```\n   781â†’cloche shutdown\n   782â†’```\n   783â†’\n   784â†’## Project Layout\n   785â†’\n   786â†’```\n   787â†’my-project/\n   788â†’â”œâ”€â”€ .cloche/\n   789â†’â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ develop.cloche        # Container workflow\n   790â†’â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ host.cloche           # Host orchestration workflow\n   791â†’â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ Dockerfile            # Container image definition\n   792â†’â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ config.toml           # Project configuration\n   793â†’â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ prompts/              # Prompt templates\n   794â†’â”‚   â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ implement.md\n   795â†’â”‚   â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ fix.md\n   796â†’â”‚   â”‚   â””â”€â”€ update-docs.md\n   797â†’â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ scripts/              # Host-side scripts\n   798â†’â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ overrides/            # Files copied on top of /workspace/\n   799â†’â”‚   â”‚   â””â”€â”€ CLAUDE.md         # Container-specific CLAUDE.md (optional)\n   800â†’â”‚   â””â”€â”€ <run-id>/             # Runtime state (gitignored)\n   801â†’â”‚       â”œâ”€â”€ prompt.txt        # User prompt\n   802â†’â”‚       â”œâ”€â”€ context.json      # Shared key-value store (cloche get/set)\n   803â†’â”‚       â”œâ”€â”€ output/\n   804â†’â”‚       â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ full.log      # Unified log\n   805â†’â”‚       â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ test.log      # Per-step script output\n   806â†’â”‚       â”‚   â””â”€â”€ llm-impl.log  # Per-step LLM conversation\n   807â†’â”‚       â”œâ”€â”€ attempt_count/    # Retry counters for max_attempts\n   808â†’â”‚       â””â”€â”€ history.log       # Step execution log\n   809â†’â”œâ”€â”€ src/                      # Project source (untouched by Cloche)\n   810â†’â””â”€â”€ .git/\n   811â†’```\n   812â†’\n   813â†’## Daemon Configuration\n   814â†’\n   815â†’| Variable | Default | Description |\n   816â†’|----------|---------|-------------|\n   817â†’| `CLOCHE_LISTEN` | `unix:///tmp/cloche.sock` | Listen address |\n   818â†’| `CLOCHE_DB` | `cloche.db` | SQLite database path |\n   819â†’| `CLOCHE_RUNTIME` | `docker` | `docker` or `local` (subprocess, for dev only) |\n   820â†’| `CLOCHE_IMAGE` | `cloche-agent:latest` | Default Docker image |\n   821â†’| `CLOCHE_HTTP` | _(unset)_ | HTTP address for web dashboard. Not started unless set. |\n   822â†’| `CLOCHE_AGENT_PATH` | _(auto)_ | Path to `cloche-agent` binary (local runtime) |\n   823â†’| `CLOCHE_LLM_COMMAND` | _(unset)_ | Command for LLM calls (evolution, merge conflicts) |\n   824â†’| `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` | _(unset)_ | Passed into Docker containers |\n   825â†’| `CLOCHE_EXTRA_MOUNTS` | _(unset)_ | Extra bind mounts (comma-separated `host:container`) |\n   826â†’| `CLOCHE_EXTRA_ENV` | _(unset)_ | Extra env vars (comma-separated `KEY=VALUE`) |\n   827â†’\n   828â†’### Client Configuration\n   829â†’\n   830â†’| Variable | Default | Description |\n   831â†’|----------|---------|-------------|\n   832â†’| `CLOCHE_ADDR` | `unix:///tmp/cloche.sock` | Daemon gRPC address |\n   833â†’| `CLOCHE_HTTP` | `localhost:8080` | Daemon HTTP address |\n   834â†’\n   835â†’## Dockerfile Requirements\n   836â†’\n   837â†’The container image must have:\n   838â†’- `cloche-agent` binary at `/usr/local/bin/cloche-agent`\n   839â†’- `git` installed\n   840â†’- An `agent` user (cloche wraps commands with `chown` + `su agent`)\n   841â†’- `/workspace` as the working directory\n   842â†’- Your project's build dependencies and the agent binary (e.g. `claude`)\n   843â†’\n   844â†’## Build Commands\n   845â†’\n   846â†’```\n   847â†’make build          # Build all binaries to bin/\n   848â†’make test           # Run all tests\n   849â†’make test-short     # Run tests (skip slow ones)\n   850â†’make lint           # Run go vet\n   851â†’make proto          # Regenerate gRPC code from protobuf\n   852â†’make docker-build   # Build the cloche-agent Docker image\n   853â†’make install        # Build, install to ~/.local/bin/, restart daemon\n   854â†’make clean          # Remove bin/\n   855â†’```\n   856â†’"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01Vxzyb14uzC2mAanCrLUN87","session_id":"5ad92cb8-7573-48d9-ae42-414182ed763c","uuid":"fe7371f4-edf5-4ee6-9408-d6722ad6b441"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01XD6u43z6XiPesB7pPAd8FE","type":"tool_result","content":"     1â†’# Project Pages Design\n     2â†’\n     3â†’**Date:** 2026-03-06\n     4â†’**Status:** Design\n     5â†’\n     6â†’## Problem\n     7â†’\n     8â†’The projects landing page shows only health dots and a \"View Runs\" link. There is no\n     9â†’dedicated project page. Useful project-level information and controls are either missing\n    10â†’or buried in other views.\n    11â†’\n    12â†’## Goal\n    13â†’\n    14â†’Add a dedicated `/projects/{name}` page with four panels:\n    15â†’\n    16â†’1. **Orchestrator control** â€” view status, enable/disable the auto-poll loop, override concurrency\n    17â†’2. **Project info** â€” Docker image, prompt file evolution history, project version\n    18â†’3. **Tasks** â€” live task pipeline view showing discovered tasks, their status, and assigned runs\n    19â†’4. **Workflow view** â€” read-only DAG of steps/wires, drillable to prompt/script content\n    20â†’\n    21â†’## Route\n    22â†’\n    23â†’```\n    24â†’GET /projects/{name}\n    25â†’```\n    26â†’\n    27â†’`{name}` is the project label (same string used in `/api/projects/{name}/trigger`).\n    28â†’The handler resolves the label back to a project directory via `projectLabels()`.\n    29â†’\n    30â†’Project cards on the landing page link to `/projects/{name}`. The project page\n    31â†’includes a compact recent-runs strip (last 10 dots) and a \"View all runs\" link to\n    32â†’`/projects/{name}/runs` for the filtered runs list.\n    33â†’\n    34â†’## Panel 1: Orchestrator Control\n    35â†’\n    36â†’### Display\n    37â†’- Status line: `Enabled / Disabled`, in-flight run count, concurrency limit\n    38â†’- Toggle button: **Enable** / **Disable** (controls the auto-poll loop for this project)\n    39â†’- Concurrency override: number input + **Apply** button (runtime only, resets on daemon restart)\n    40â†’\n    41â†’### API additions\n    42â†’\n    43â†’```\n    44â†’GET  /api/projects/{name}/orchestrator\n    45â†’POST /api/projects/{name}/orchestrator/start\n    46â†’POST /api/projects/{name}/orchestrator/stop\n    47â†’POST /api/projects/{name}/orchestrator/concurrency   body: {\"concurrency\": N}\n    48â†’```\n    49â†’\n    50â†’`GET` response:\n    51â†’```json\n    52â†’{\n    53â†’  \"enabled\": true,\n    54â†’  \"in_flight\": 1,\n    55â†’  \"concurrency\": 2\n    56â†’}\n    57â†’```\n    58â†’\n    59â†’The orchestrator currently has no per-project enable/disable concept. We add an\n    60â†’`enabled` flag to `ProjectConfig` (default true when registered). Start/stop toggle\n    61â†’this flag. When disabled, `Run()` returns 0 without dispatching.\n    62â†’\n    63â†’Concurrency override updates `ProjectConfig.Concurrency` in memory only.\n    64â†’\n    65â†’The Handler needs a reference to the `*orchestrator.Orchestrator` (or a minimal\n    66â†’interface exposing `Status(dir)`, `SetEnabled(dir, bool)`, `SetConcurrency(dir, int)`,\n    67â†’`InFlight(dir)`). Wire this in via a `HandlerOption`.\n    68â†’\n    69â†’## Panel 2: Project Info\n    70â†’\n    71â†’### Display\n    72â†’- **Docker image**: read the `FROM` line(s) from `.cloche/Dockerfile`. Show the last\n    73â†’  non-builder stage's base image (i.e. the stage that produces the final image).\n    74â†’- **Project version**: integer, sourced from `.cloche/version` (see Project Versioning\n    75â†’  design). Display as `v3`.\n    76â†’- **Prompt files**: for each file under `.cloche/prompts/`, show:\n    77â†’  - Current file contents in a collapsible accordion\n    78â†’  - Git commit history (short SHA, date, message)\n    79â†’  - Click a commit entry to expand and show a unified diff inline\n    80â†’\n    81â†’### API additions\n    82â†’\n    83â†’```\n    84â†’GET /api/projects/{name}/info\n    85â†’```\n    86â†’\n    87â†’Response:\n    88â†’```json\n    89â†’{\n    90â†’  \"docker_image\": \"ubuntu:24.04\",\n    91â†’  \"version\": 3,\n    92â†’  \"prompt_files\": [\n    93â†’    {\n    94â†’      \"path\": \".cloche/prompts/implement.md\",\n    95â†’      \"content\": \"Full text of the prompt file...\",\n    96â†’      \"history\": [\n    97â†’        {\"sha\": \"abc1234\", \"date\": \"2026-03-05\", \"message\": \"evolution: tighten scope\"},\n    98â†’        {\"sha\": \"def5678\", \"date\": \"2026-03-01\", \"message\": \"init\"}\n    99â†’      ]\n   100â†’    }\n   101â†’  ]\n   102â†’}\n   103â†’```\n   104â†’\n   105â†’Implementation: run `git log --follow --oneline -- <file>` in the project directory\n   106â†’via `exec.Command`. Diff for a specific commit loaded lazily on click via:\n   107â†’\n   108â†’```\n   109â†’GET /api/projects/{name}/info/prompt-diff?file=.cloche/prompts/implement.md&sha=abc1234\n   110â†’```\n   111â†’\n   112â†’Returns plain text unified diff (`git show <sha> -- <file>`).\n   113â†’\n   114â†’## Panel 3: Tasks\n   115â†’\n   116â†’### Display\n   117â†’- Table showing discovered tasks: Task ID, Title, Status, Assigned (yes/no), Run link\n   118â†’- Status badges: `open` (running style), `closed` (succeeded style), other (pending style)\n   119â†’- Auto-refreshes every 5 seconds via polling\n   120â†’- Shows \"No tasks discovered\" when the project has no list-tasks output\n   121â†’\n   122â†’### API\n   123â†’\n   124â†’```\n   125â†’GET /api/projects/{name}/tasks\n   126â†’```\n   127â†’\n   128â†’Returns the task pipeline state for the project's orchestration loop.\n   129â†’\n   130â†’### Runs page changes\n   131â†’\n   132â†’- `list-tasks` workflow runs are hidden from the Runs page (both server-rendered and\n   133â†’  JS-rendered views)\n   134â†’- Runs with the same `task_id` are grouped under a task header row\n   135â†’- The task header shows an aggregate status badge (active statuses running/pending outweigh terminal ones; among terminal-only runs the most recently started determines the result)\n   136â†’- The `task_id` and `task_status` fields are included in the `/api/runs` JSON response\n   137â†’- Runs without a `task_id` appear ungrouped below task groups\n   138â†’\n   139â†’## Panel 4: Workflow View\n   140â†’\n   141â†’### Display\n   142â†’- Two-level tab navigation:\n   143â†’  - **Location tabs** (Container / Host) shown when both container and host workflows exist\n   144â†’  - **Workflow tabs** shown when the active location has multiple workflows\n   145â†’- Per workflow: a read-only DAG rendered client-side\n   146â†’  - Nodes = steps, rendered as boxes showing step name + type icon (agent ًں¤– / script ًں“œ / workflow ًں”پ)\n   147â†’  - Edges = wires, labeled with the result name (e.g. `success`, `fail`)\n   148â†’  - Terminal nodes `done` and `abort` rendered distinctly\n   149â†’- Clicking a step node opens a right-side **drawer panel** (CSS slide-in):\n   150â†’  - Step name and type\n   151â†’  - Results list\n   152â†’  - `max_attempts` if set\n   153â†’  - For agent steps: full content of the referenced prompt file (loaded on demand)\n   154â†’  - For script steps: the `command`/`script` string or contents of the referenced script file\n   155â†’  - For host script steps: contents of a referenced script file under `.cloche/scripts/` (text files only); the content panel is hidden when no displayable content is available\n   156â†’  - For workflow steps: displays the dispatched workflow name\n   157â†’  - Drawer closes via X button or Escape, returning focus to the DAG without page reload\n   158â†’\n   159â†’### DAG rendering\n   160â†’Client-side Sugiyama-style layered layout with no external library. Steps are assigned to\n   161â†’layers via longest-path from sources, then ordered within each layer using barycenter\n   162â†’heuristic (4 forward/backward passes) to minimize edge crossings. Layout flows\n   163â†’left-to-right with SVG Bezier curve edges.\n   164â†’\n   165â†’Non-success wires (any result not in `success`, `ok`, `done`, `pass`) are offset\n   166â†’vertically below the main flow so they don't overlap the happy-path edges. These wires\n   167â†’use a distinct failure color and reduced opacity (`dag-edge-nonsuccess` class) with a\n   168â†’matching arrowhead marker.\n   169â†’\n   170â†’When multiple wires target the same terminal (`done` or `abort`), they merge into a\n   171â†’collector bus: individual curves from each source converge on a vertical dashed line,\n   172â†’which feeds a single arrow into the terminal node. Non-success wires within a merge bus\n   173â†’are offset to their own vertical positions, and the collector line extends to cover them.\n   174â†’This reduces wire clutter as graphs grow in complexity.\n   175â†’\n   176â†’The DAG container scrolls horizontally when the graph exceeds the panel width.\n   177â†’\n   178â†’### API additions\n   179â†’\n   180â†’```\n   181â†’GET /api/projects/{name}/workflows\n   182â†’```\n   183â†’\n   184â†’Response:\n   185â†’```json\n   186â†’[\n   187â†’  {\n   188â†’    \"name\": \"develop\",\n   189â†’    \"file\": \".cloche/develop.cloche\",\n   190â†’    \"location\": \"container\",\n   191â†’    \"steps\": [\n   192â†’      {\n   193â†’        \"name\": \"implement\",\n   194â†’        \"type\": \"agent\",\n   195â†’        \"results\": [\"success\", \"fail\"],\n   196â†’        \"config\": {\"prompt\": \".cloche/prompts/implement.md\", \"max_attempts\": null}\n   197â†’      },\n   198â†’      ...\n   199â†’    ],\n   200â†’    \"wires\": [\n   201â†’      {\"from\": \"implement\", \"result\": \"success\", \"to\": \"test\"},\n   202â†’      ...\n   203â†’    ],\n   204â†’    \"entry_step\": \"implement\"\n   205â†’  }\n   206â†’]\n   207â†’```\n   208â†’\n   209â†’The `location` field is either `\"container\"` or `\"host\"`. Host workflows are parsed from\n   210â†’`.cloche/host.cloche` and included in the same response.\n   211â†’\n   212â†’```\n   213â†’GET /api/projects/{name}/workflows/{workflow}/steps/{step}/content\n   214â†’```\n   215â†’\n   216â†’Returns the raw content of the prompt file or script for that step (plain text).\n   217â†’For `run` steps, only serves content from text files under `.cloche/scripts/`;\n   218â†’file references outside that directory or binary files return an empty response.\n   219â†’Inline command strings (not file references) return empty unless they reference\n   220â†’a script file under `.cloche/scripts/`.\n   221â†’\n   222â†’## Template / file changes\n   223â†’\n   224â†’- New template: `templates/project_detail.html`\n   225â†’- New page registered in `NewHandler`: `\"project_detail\"`\n   226â†’- New routes registered in `NewHandler` mux\n   227â†’- Handler struct gains an optional orchestrator interface field (via `HandlerOption`)\n   228â†’\n   229â†’## Not in scope\n   230â†’\n   231â†’- Editing workflow files from the UI\n   232â†’- Evolution history of workflow structure (just current state)\n   233â†’- Persisting concurrency overrides to disk\n   234â†’"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01Vxzyb14uzC2mAanCrLUN87","session_id":"5ad92cb8-7573-48d9-ae42-414182ed763c","uuid":"3ede478b-87f6-4c37-adb5-268812d4fa66"}
