{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01VUEAbQq8X1ZmgzkuZjLVYb","type":"tool_result","content":"     1â†’# Next Features Design\n     2â†’\n     3â†’Date: 2026-03-03\n     4â†’\n     5â†’This document captures the design for the five features listed in PROJECT.md:\n     6â†’Orchestrator, Indicator Lights, Web Dashboard, Log Contents, and Container Deletion.\n     7â†’\n     8â†’## 1. Orchestrator\n     9â†’\n    10â†’**Goal:** Automate work dispatch â€” pull ready tasks from a task tracker, generate\n    11â†’prompts via LLM, kick off workflow runs, and manage the merge queue for landing\n    12â†’completed work.\n    13â†’\n    14â†’**Location:** Built into `cloched` (no new binary).\n    15â†’\n    16â†’**Components:**\n    17â†’\n    18â†’### TaskTracker Port\n    19â†’\n    20â†’New interface `ports.TaskTracker`:\n    21â†’\n    22â†’```go\n    23â†’type Task struct {\n    24â†’    ID          string\n    25â†’    Title       string\n    26â†’    Description string\n    27â†’    Labels      []string\n    28â†’    Priority    int\n    29â†’}\n    30â†’\n    31â†’type TaskTracker interface {\n    32â†’    ListReady(ctx context.Context, project string) ([]Task, error)\n    33â†’    Claim(ctx context.Context, taskID string) error\n    34â†’    Complete(ctx context.Context, taskID string) error\n    35â†’    Fail(ctx context.Context, taskID string) error\n    36â†’}\n    37â†’```\n    38â†’\n    39â†’First adapter: Beads. Future adapters: Jira, Linear, GitHub Issues.\n    40â†’\n    41â†’Tasks returned by `ListReady` are ordered by priority (highest first).\n    42â†’\n    43â†’### PromptGenerator\n    44â†’\n    45â†’Takes a `Task` and project context, calls the project's configured LLM to generate\n    46â†’a prompt suitable for the workflow. The generated prompt is passed to the workflow run\n    47â†’as the `--prompt` argument.\n    48â†’\n    49â†’### Orchestration Loop\n    50â†’\n    51â†’Event-driven, triggers on:\n    52â†’1. Daemon startup â€” check all projects for ready work.\n    53â†’2. Run completion â€” after a run finishes, check the completed run's project for more work.\n    54â†’3. `cloche loop` CLI command â€” manual trigger, checks all projects.\n    55â†’\n    56â†’On trigger:\n    57â†’1. For each registered project with orchestration enabled:\n    58â†’2. Query task tracker for ready work (priority-ordered).\n    59â†’3. Check in-flight run count against per-project concurrency limit.\n    60â†’4. For each available slot: claim the highest-priority task, generate prompt, dispatch run.\n    61â†’\n    62â†’### Configuration\n    63â†’\n    64â†’Per-project in `.cloche/config.toml` (or similar):\n    65â†’\n    66â†’```toml\n    67â†’[orchestration]\n    68â†’enabled = true\n    69â†’tracker = \"beads\"\n    70â†’concurrency = 1\n    71â†’workflow = \"develop\"\n    72â†’```\n    73â†’\n    74â†’### Concurrency\n    75â†’\n    76â†’Per-project limits. Project A with limit 2 and project B with limit 1 can have up to\n    77â†’3 runs in-flight simultaneously.\n    78â†’\n    79â†’### Merge Queue\n    80â†’\n    81â†’When a run completes successfully (`done` result), the orchestrator enqueues its\n    82â†’branch (`cloche/<runID>`) into a per-project merge queue.\n    83â†’\n    84â†’**Serialization:** Per-project. Each project processes one merge at a time. Different\n    85â†’projects can merge in parallel. Queue is FIFO.\n    86â†’\n    87â†’**Merge execution:** The orchestrator picks the next branch from the queue and hands\n    88â†’it to an LLM agent running on the host (not in a container). The agent operates in\n    89â†’a git worktree and:\n    90â†’\n    91â†’1. Pulls latest main into the worktree.\n    92â†’2. Merges the feature branch.\n    93â†’3. Resolves any conflicts.\n    94â†’4. Runs validation if configured (tests, build).\n    95â†’5. If clean: merges to main, cleans up the worktree, deletes the branch.\n    96â†’6. If unresolvable: reports failure.\n    97â†’\n    98â†’**On the host via worktree:** Merges need direct access to the real git repo. A git\n    99â†’worktree is created for the merge, then removed after completion. Lighter weight\n   100â†’than spinning up a container.\n   101â†’\n   102â†’**Failure handling:** If the merge agent can't resolve conflicts, the merge is marked\n   103â†’as failed. The branch is preserved. The user is notified via the dashboard/indicator\n   104â†’lights. No automatic retry â€” human intervenes.\n   105â†’\n   106â†’**Post-merge:** After a successful merge, the branch is deleted and the orchestrator\n   107â†’triggers a check for more work (same event-driven model as run completion).\n   108â†’\n   109â†’---\n   110â†’\n   111â†’## 2. Indicator Lights\n   112â†’\n   113â†’**Goal:** Per-project health indicators based on recent run history.\n   114â†’\n   115â†’### Health Calculator\n   116â†’\n   117â†’Domain-level function: given the last N runs for a project, return health status:\n   118â†’- **Green** â€” all runs passed\n   119â†’- **Yellow** â€” some runs failed\n   120â†’- **Red** â€” all runs failed\n   121â†’- **Grey** â€” no runs yet\n   122â†’- **Blue** â€” all runs currently in-progress (no completed runs in window)\n   123â†’\n   124â†’Window size N is configurable per-project, default 5.\n   125â†’\n   126â†’### API\n   127â†’\n   128â†’Extend `GET /api/projects` to include a `health` field per project:\n   129â†’\n   130â†’```json\n   131â†’{\n   132â†’  \"name\": \"my-project\",\n   133â†’  \"health\": {\n   134â†’    \"status\": \"yellow\",\n   135â†’    \"passed\": 3,\n   136â†’    \"failed\": 2,\n   137â†’    \"total\": 5\n   138â†’  }\n   139â†’}\n   140â†’```\n   141â†’\n   142â†’### CLI\n   143â†’\n   144â†’`cloche health` â€” table of all projects with health status, passed/failed counts.\n   145â†’\n   146â†’### Dashboard\n   147â†’\n   148â†’Colored dot next to each project name on the landing page.\n   149â†’\n   150â†’---\n   151â†’\n   152â†’## 3. Web Dashboard Enhancements\n   153â†’\n   154â†’**Goal:** Project-centric landing page with health indicators, run history, and quick\n   155â†’actions. Enabled by default.\n   156â†’\n   157â†’### Landing Page\n   158â†’\n   159â†’Replace the current runs-list with a project overview. Each project card shows:\n   160â†’- Indicator light (health status color)\n   161â†’- Success rate (e.g. \"8/10 recent runs passed\")\n   162â†’- Mini run history â€” last ~10 runs as colored dots (green/red)\n   163â†’- Active run count\n   164â†’- Quick actions: \"Trigger orchestrator\" button, \"View runs\" link\n   165â†’\n   166â†’### Default Activation\n   167â†’\n   168â†’Dashboard starts automatically with `cloched` on default port `:8080`.\n   169â†’Overridable via `CLOCHE_HTTP` env var. Disable with `CLOCHE_HTTP=off`.\n   170â†’\n   171â†’### Existing Pages\n   172â†’\n   173â†’Runs list and run detail pages preserved, accessible per-project from the landing page.\n   174â†’\n   175â†’---\n   176â†’\n   177â†’## 4. Log Contents\n   178â†’\n   179â†’**Goal:** Capture all output (LLM conversations, script output, status messages) in a\n   180â†’unified log stream. Real-time streaming for active runs, archived files for completed runs.\n   181â†’\n   182â†’### Unified Log Stream\n   183â†’\n   184â†’The agent captures everything chronologically to `.cloche/output/full.log` with\n   185â†’structured entries:\n   186â†’\n   187â†’```\n   188â†’[2026-03-03T10:15:00Z] [status] step_started: build\n   189â†’[2026-03-03T10:15:01Z] [script] + npm run build\n   190â†’[2026-03-03T10:15:02Z] [script] Build successful\n   191â†’[2026-03-03T10:15:03Z] [status] step_completed: build -> done\n   192â†’[2026-03-03T10:15:04Z] [status] step_started: implement\n   193â†’[2026-03-03T10:15:05Z] [llm] Claude: I'll start by reading the relevant files...\n   194â†’[2026-03-03T10:15:06Z] [llm] Claude: [tool_use: Read file src/main.go]\n   195â†’```\n   196â†’\n   197â†’LLM output and script output are included inline in the unified stream. This is the\n   198â†’primary view for understanding what's happening.\n   199â†’\n   200â†’### Per-Step Files\n   201â†’\n   202â†’Additionally, per-step files are written for convenience:\n   203â†’- `.cloche/output/llm-<step>.log` â€” LLM conversation for agent steps\n   204â†’- `.cloche/output/<step>.log` â€” script output (existing behavior)\n   205â†’\n   206â†’### Real-Time Streaming\n   207â†’\n   208â†’For active runs, the daemon pipes container stdout to web clients via Server-Sent Events\n   209â†’(SSE). The run detail page gets a live log viewer. LLM and script output are visible\n   210â†’in real-time, not just status changes.\n   211â†’\n   212â†’CLI: `cloche logs <run-id> --follow` streams the unified log in real-time.\n   213â†’\n   214â†’### Post-Run Archival\n   215â†’\n   216â†’On completion, log files extracted to `.cloche/<run-id>/output/`. SQLite index stores:\n   217â†’run ID, step name, log file path, size, timestamps.\n   218â†’\n   219â†’### CLI Enhancements\n   220â†’\n   221â†’`cloche logs <run-id>` shows the full unified log.\n   222â†’`cloche logs <run-id> --step <name>` filters to a specific step.\n   223â†’`cloche logs <run-id> --follow` streams in real-time.\n   224â†’\n   225â†’---\n   226â†’\n   227â†’## 5. Container Deletion\n   228â†’\n   229â†’**Goal:** Keep failed containers for debugging. Show retained containers in the dashboard.\n   230â†’CLI command to delete them.\n   231â†’\n   232â†’### Retention Policy\n   233â†’\n   234â†’- Failed runs: container always kept (automatic).\n   235â†’- Successful runs: container auto-deleted (existing behavior).\n   236â†’- `--keep-container` flag preserved: keeps container regardless of outcome.\n   237â†’\n   238â†’### Container Tracking\n   239â†’\n   240â†’When a container is kept, record in SQLite: Docker container ID, run ID, project,\n   241â†’creation time, status. Updated when container is deleted.\n   242â†’\n   243â†’### CLI Command\n   244â†’\n   245â†’`cloche delete <container-or-run-id>` â€” accepts Docker container name/ID or run ID.\n   246â†’Calls daemon via gRPC to remove the container and update the store.\n   247â†’Single container at a time.\n   248â†’\n   249â†’### gRPC\n   250â†’\n   251â†’New RPC: `DeleteContainer(container_id)` â€” daemon calls `docker rm` and updates store.\n   252â†’\n   253â†’### Dashboard\n   254â†’\n   255â†’Run detail page shows whether container is still available. If so, shows \"Delete\n   256â†’container\" button. Project overview shows count of retained containers.\n   257â†’\n   258â†’---\n   259â†’\n   260â†’## Feature Dependencies\n   261â†’\n   262â†’The features have some natural ordering based on dependencies:\n   263â†’\n   264â†’1. **Container Deletion** â€” standalone, no dependencies on other features.\n   265â†’2. **Indicator Lights** â€” standalone domain logic, needed by Dashboard.\n   266â†’3. **Log Contents** â€” standalone, changes agent + daemon. Needed by Dashboard for log viewer.\n   267â†’4. **Web Dashboard** â€” depends on Indicator Lights and Log Contents for full functionality.\n   268â†’5. **Orchestrator** â€” depends on a working task tracker. Largest feature. Can be developed in parallel with 1-3. Includes the merge queue subsystem.\n   269â†’"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01Vxzyb14uzC2mAanCrLUN87","session_id":"5ad92cb8-7573-48d9-ae42-414182ed763c","uuid":"b7adeb28-b3ec-47e5-9350-b1491eb48703"}
